"""
MKT Context Commentary — Exodus 39–40
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-39-40.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/exodus.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/exodus.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/exodus.json (existing entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- Priestly garments (ch39) analyzed as royal dress with Egyptian high-priest parallels
- "Just as the LORD commanded Moses" refrain (ch39-40) treated as a Genesis-creation echo
- The twelve-stone breastplate discussed against ANE gemstone-pectoral parallels
- The first-day-of-the-first-month setting (40:2/17) identified as New Year's Day, year 2
- The glory-cloud descent (40:34-35) treated as the theological climax of all of Exodus
- Cloud/fire guidance (40:36-38) identified as the transition into the wilderness wandering
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
    "39": {
        "1": "<p>Exodus 39 records the completion and presentation of the priestly garments, mirroring the instructions in ch.28. The 'vestments for service in the sanctuary' (<em>bigdê haššĕrād</em>) were not merely functional clothing but a complete symbolic system: the high priest embodied Israel before YHWH, wearing the twelve tribes on his chest and shoulders. Blue, purple, and scarlet (<em>tĕkēlet, ʾargāmān, tôlaʿat šānî</em>) were the most expensive dyes in the ancient world — blue from the murex snail (Phoenician sea-snail), purple similarly, and scarlet from the coccus worm — making the priestly vestments a visual declaration of the value YHWH placed on Israel's access to him.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The ephod was the central garment of the high priest's vestments — a vest-like garment of extraordinary workmanship worn over the blue robe. The combination of woven gold threads with blue, purple, scarlet, and fine twisted linen made it the most elaborate textile in the ancient world outside of royal contexts. Egyptian high priests also wore elaborate pectorals and garments that signified their mediatorial role between the divine and human realms; the Israelite ephod belongs to this ancient tradition of priestly vestiture as cosmic symbolism while being distinct in its covenant-specific meaning.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The gold threads woven into the ephod fabric were produced by hammering sheet gold into thin foil, cutting it into strips, and weaving these metallic threads through the linen. This goldwork technique is attested in ancient Egyptian textiles; gold-wrapped linen threads have been found in Egyptian royal burials. The technique required extraordinary skill and patience, explaining why Bezalel and Oholiab were specifically credited with divine gift for craftsmanship (Exod 35:30-36:2). The result would have been a garment that caught and reflected light — visually radiating glory when worn.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The shoulder pieces (<em>kĕtēpôt</em>) of the ephod were functional — joining the front and back panels at the shoulders — and symbolic: they bore the two onyx stones engraved with the tribal names (vv.6-7), making the priest's literal shoulders the bearer of Israel's weight before YHWH. The image anticipates the NT's shepherd who carries the sheep on his shoulders (Luke 15:5) and Christ as the one who bears the burden of his people's sin (Isa 53:4-6; 1 Pet 2:24). The priestly bearing-of-the-tribes is a physical enactment of the intercessory role.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The decorative waistband (<em>ḥēšeb</em>) of the ephod was woven as an integral part of the garment — not a separate belt but a woven band that cinched and completed the garment's structure. Its description as 'the same materials' (gold, blue, purple, scarlet, linen) emphasizes the unity and consistency of the high priest's vesture as a complete symbolic system. Ancient vestiary texts from Egypt describe similar decorative bands on priestly garments, but the Israelite version is unique in combining gold thread with the covenant colors.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The two onyx stones (<em>ʾabnê šōham</em>) mounted in gold filigree settings and engraved with the twelve tribal names (six per stone) are described as 'signet-seal' engravings — the same technique used to engrave personal seals for legal authentication. Each tribal name impressed on gold-mounted gems constitutes a kind of royal seal: the high priest carries Israel's twelve tribes to YHWH as a certified, authenticated document. The use of gold filigree (<em>mišbĕṣôt zāhāb</em>, literally 'gold braiding/setting') shows the jewelry-level craftsmanship involved.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Memorial stones for the Israelites' (<em>ʾabnê zikkārôn libnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) — the shoulder-stones are explicitly called 'remembrance/memorial stones': they ensure that YHWH 'remembers' (in the covenantal sense of active attention and faithfulness) all twelve tribes when the high priest enters the sanctuary. The same word <em>zikkārôn</em> is used for the Passover as a 'memorial' (Exod 12:14) and for the trumpets blown to bring Israel to YHWH's remembrance (Num 10:10). Priestly intercession is enacted remembrance: appearing before YHWH carrying Israel's name is how YHWH is reminded (in human terms) of his covenant obligations.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The breastplate (<em>ḥōšen</em>) is described as made by the same technique as the ephod — woven goldwork — and folded double to form a square pouch. The twelve gemstones set in it, each representing a tribe, make it the most jeweled object in the tabernacle complex. Elaborate pectorals (chest ornaments) were central to Egyptian priestly and royal dress; the Pharaoh wore a pectoral as a symbol of divine protection and cosmic authority. The Israelite breastplate inverts the Egyptian symbolism: it is not the priest's protection but Israel's identification — the priest bears the people, not a divine emblem.</p>",
        "9": "<p>A 'span' (<em>zeret</em>) was the distance between the outstretched thumb and little finger — approximately 9 inches (23 cm). The double-folded pouch formed a square, creating an interior pocket for the Urim and Thummim (v.21; see below). The perfect square shape may be significant: the altar of burnt offering was also square (Exod 27:1), and the most holy place of the tabernacle was a cube (10×10×10 cubits). Square/cubic proportions in the tabernacle reflect divine perfection and order; the breastplate's square shape aligns it with the other symbols of perfect holiness.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The twelve gemstones are arranged in four rows of three, corresponding to the twelve tribal encampments around the tabernacle (Num 2). The identification of the specific gemstones is uncertain; ancient Hebrew gem terminology does not map precisely onto modern mineralogy. The first row: <em>ʾōdem</em> (carnelian/ruby), <em>piṭdāh</em> (topaz/chrysolite), <em>bāreqet</em> (green stone/emerald). These were precious stones available through trade networks in the ancient Near East — Egypt was a major conduit for gemstone trade from Ethiopia, Arabia, and as far as India.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Second row: <em>nōpek</em> (turquoise or carbuncle), <em>sappîr</em> (lapis lazuli — see Exod 24:10 where YHWH's throne-pavement is sapphire/lapis), <em>yāhălōm</em> (moonstone, onyx, or diamond). Lapis lazuli was among the most valued stones in the ancient world, associated with the sky and divine presence; its presence on the breastplate links the priestly intercession to the divine throne. The most complete ancient parallel to the twelve-stone pectoral is the Egyptian New Kingdom royal pectoral, which also used semi-precious stones to signify cosmic order and divine protection.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Third row: <em>lešem</em> (jacinth or amber), <em>šĕbô</em> (agate or banded stone), <em>ʾaḥlāmāh</em> (amethyst). Amethyst (<em>ʾaḥlāmāh</em>, from the root meaning 'dream') was associated with clarity of vision in the ancient world; the Greeks named it from their belief that it prevented intoxication. The placement of amethyst in the high priest's breastplate may reflect a tradition connecting the priest's vision/discernment (connected also to the Urim and Thummim) with this stone's cultural associations.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Fourth row: <em>taršîš</em> (beryl or yellow topaz), <em>šōham</em> (onyx — the same stone as the shoulder pieces, v.6), <em>yāšpēh</em> (jasper). The inclusion of onyx in both the shoulder pieces and the breastplate creates a visual and material unity between the two sets of tribal memorials. The 'gold filigree' settings appear again — the same term (<em>mišbĕṣôt</em>) as in the shoulder-piece settings, confirming the consistent goldsmithing standard throughout the high priest's regalia.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'There was one stone for each of the twelve tribes of Israel — each engraved like a signet with the name of one of the twelve tribes' — the precision of the tribal correspondence is deliberately highlighted. No tribe was omitted; the high priest carried all twelve before YHWH without exception. This comprehensive representation anticipates NT imagery of the high priest who intercedes for all his people without partiality (Heb 7:25: 'he always lives to intercede for them'). The Revelation of John's new Jerusalem has twelve foundation stones (Rev 21:19-20) corresponding to the twelve apostles, possibly echoing the breastplate's twelve stones.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The chains of pure gold (<em>šarŝĕrōt ʿăbōt maʿăśēh zāhāb ṭāhôr</em>) that attach the breastplate to the ephod are described as 'braided' or 'twisted' — intricate goldwork that required the skill of a master jeweler. The multiple attachment points (four gold rings, two braided chains, blue cord at the bottom) created a system of redundant security: the breastplate was not just draped but fastened to ensure it remained in precise position during priestly service. The elaborate attachment system reflects the conviction that the high priest's bearing of Israel before YHWH is too important to risk displacement.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The gold settings and rings at the upper corners of the breastplate form part of the complex attachment system to the ephod. The detailed description of each attachment point (four rings, two chains, two shoulders of the ephod, blue cord below) ensures that any craftsman could reproduce the design. This level of technical specification in sacred texts is unusual in the ancient world; the tabernacle instructions treat the construction details as part of the revelation, not just the theological meaning. Getting the design right was not optional.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The braided chains connect the breastplate's upper rings to the shoulder pieces — tying the chest-level tribal representation to the shoulder-level one. Both the shoulder onyx stones and the breastplate gems carry the tribal names; the chains linking them make the whole priestly vestiture a unified system. The chains' function as connector between the two sets of tribal memorials emphasizes the organic unity of Israel's twelve tribes in the priestly representation: they are neither 12 separate entities nor an undifferentiated mass, but a unified covenant people whose constituent parts are individually named.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The technical description of the chain attachment to the ephod's shoulder pieces demonstrates that the instructions of Exod 28 have been precisely followed. The repetitive technical language in ch.39 echoes the instructions in ch.25-28 with deliberate verbal mirroring — everything that was commanded is being executed. This 'as commanded' structure (see v.32, 42, 43 and throughout ch.40) mirrors the language of Genesis 1's creation week: 'And God saw that it was good' after each completion. The tabernacle's construction is being presented as a new creation enacted by a new Adam (Israel) doing exactly what the Creator specified.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The lower rings of the breastplate are attached 'on the inner side facing the ephod' — a detail ensuring the breastplate hangs flush against the priest's body rather than swinging free. The phrase 'inner side' (<em>ʿēber bêt hammeʿîl</em>) — literally 'the side toward the robe' — shows the maker's attention to how the completed garment will function when worn. The priestly garments were designed to work as an integrated system; each component was specified in relation to the others. This integration is both functional and theological: the high priest is not wearing unrelated items but a total symbolic system.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The two additional gold rings on the ephod's lower front shoulders receive the lower attachment of the breastplate, preventing the breastplate from swinging outward during movement. The term <em>mulaʿmāt pānāyw</em> ('on its front side, near its join') shows the craftsman's attention to the joint mechanics. Ancient Egyptian priestly vestments similarly used multiple points of attachment for pectorals to ensure they remained precisely positioned during ritual movement — the same functional logic operating across different cultural expressions of the priest-as-mediator concept.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The Urim and Thummim (<em>hāʾûrîm wĕhattummîm</em>) were placed inside the breastplate (Exod 28:30), which is why it was also called the 'breastplate of judgment/decision' (<em>ḥōšen hammiš-pāṭ</em>). Their exact nature is unknown — possibly two stones or objects used for oracular lot-casting — but their function was clear: discerning YHWH's will in cases where human judgment was insufficient (Num 27:21; 1 Sam 28:6). The 'blue cord' binding breastplate to ephod ensures they remain unified: the priestly bearer of Israel (ephod) and the priestly discerner of YHWH's will (breastplate with Urim/Thummim) are one integrated office.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The blue robe (<em>mĕʿîl hāʾēpôd</em>) of solid woven blue was worn under the ephod and covered the priest's torso and arms. Blue (<em>tĕkēlet</em>), made from the Murex trunculus snail's secretion, was the most expensive of the three covenant colors — in some ancient markets more valuable by weight than gold. A garment entirely of this color would have been visually stunning and economically staggering. The blue robe's single color distinguished it from the multi-colored ephod above it, creating a visual hierarchy of the priestly vestments.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The woven neck opening 'like the neck of a soldier's tunic' (<em>pî taḥrā'</em>) with a woven reinforcing rim prevented tearing — practical durability built into a sacred garment. The tunic analogy ('soldier's tunic') is striking: it implicitly evokes the priestly role as YHWH's warrior, serving in the sanctuary as soldiers serve in battle. The priestly service had its own warfare dimension: the high priest entered the most holy place on Yom Kippur as a representative of Israel standing before divine holiness, a task as dangerous as any military engagement (hence the bells, so the people outside could hear the priest was still alive).</p>",
        "24": "<p>The pomegranates (<em>rimmōnîm</em>) on the hem of the robe were sewn from blue, purple, and scarlet yarn on fine linen — three-dimensional fabric sculptures rather than embroidered images. Pomegranates were fertility symbols throughout the ancient Near East, associated with abundance and blessing; they appear as decorative motifs in Canaanite temples, Egyptian art, and on the capitals of Solomon's temple columns (1 Kgs 7:18-20). The pomegranate's many seeds inside a red exterior made it a universal symbol of overflowing life. On the high priest's robe, they represent YHWH's blessing flowing from the sanctuary outward.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The golden bells (<em>paʿămōnê zāhāb</em>) alternating with pomegranates around the robe's hem produced sound with every movement of the priest. Sound in ANE sacred space was as significant as visual symbolism: bells, music, and chanting were all part of the sacred acoustic environment of temples. In the tabernacle context, the bells served a dual function: they announced the high priest's presence before YHWH (warning: a human is approaching sacred space) and confirmed to the people outside that the priest was still alive and moving (Exod 28:35: 'so that he will not die').</p>",
        "26": "<p>'Bell and pomegranate, bell and pomegranate, alternating all around the hem — for wear when serving' — the alternating pattern of sound (bells) and symbol (pomegranates) creates a complete sensory vocabulary: the bells produce sound that signals priestly movement; the pomegranates signal abundance and blessing. The phrase 'for wear when serving' (<em>kĕlābōš lĕšārēt</em>) emphasizes that these garments exist only for the liturgical context. The high priest's priestly identity was inseparable from his vestiture: dressed, he was the high priest; undressed, he was an ordinary mortal.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The linen tunics for Aaron and his sons — simpler garments than the high priest's elaborate vestments but still fine-quality fabric. The distinction between the high priest's multi-layered regalia and the ordinary priests' simpler garments reflects the graduated holiness structure: the high priest alone entered the most holy place, wore the most elaborate vestments, bore the Urim and Thummim. The ordinary priests served in the outer court and holy place with a subset of the high priest's vestiture. The gradation of garments visualized the gradation of sacred responsibility.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The turban (<em>miṣnepet</em>), headbands (<em>migbāʿôt</em>), and undergarments complete the priestly vestiture system from head to foot. The turban (Heb: 'something wound around') is specifically Aaron's; the headbands are the lesser priests'. Both are of fine linen — the material that throughout the ancient Near East signified purity and priestly status (Egyptian priests wore white linen exclusively; Revelation's heavenly worshippers wear 'fine linen, bright and pure,' Rev 19:8, drawing on this tradition).</p>",
        "29": "<p>The sash (<em>ʾabnet</em>) of embroidered linen completes the list of priestly garments. The word 'embroidered' (<em>maʿăśēh rōqēm</em>) — literally 'work of a weaver/embroiderer' — is the technical term for needlework creating a multi-colored pattern on a solid fabric, as distinct from the woven pattern technique (<em>maʿăśēh ḥōšēb</em>) of the ephod. The level of textile craft required for the full priestly vestiture was extraordinary: the combination of weaving, embroidery, metalwork, gemstone-setting, and goldsmithing would have required a workshop of specialists, all of whom are credited as Spirit-gifted (Exod 35:35).</p>",
        "30": "<p>'HOLINESS TO THE LORD' (<em>qōdeš laYHWH</em>) engraved on the golden plate (<em>ṣîṣ hazzāhāb</em>, literally 'the gold gleam') is the central theological declaration of the high priesthood. The engraving technique is 'like a signet' — the same authentication-seal technique as the breastplate stones. The plate declares: this man's service is not self-appointed but divinely authorized and claimed; the high priest belongs to YHWH in the same absolute sense as the plate itself. The phrase appears elsewhere only in Zech 14:20-21, where 'HOLINESS TO THE LORD' will be inscribed on the bells of horses and cooking pots — a vision of the holy spreading from the priest to all of creation.</p>",
        "31": "<p>The blue cord attaching the golden plate to the turban ensures it sits on the priest's forehead — the same location as the tefillin/frontlets commanded for every Israelite (Exod 13:9,16) and the mark on the foreheads of Ezekiel's preserved remnant (Ezek 9:4) and Revelation's sealed servants (Rev 7:3; 14:1). The high priest's forehead-mark 'HOLINESS TO THE LORD' is the ultimate version of the covenant identity-mark: while every Israelite is commanded to bind YHWH's covenant on their foreheads, the high priest literally wears the divine name as a crown over his face, declaring his identity as wholly belonging to YHWH.</p>",
        "32": "<p>'So all the work on the tabernacle — the tent of meeting — was completed' (<em>watĕkel kol-ʿăbodat miškan ʾōhel môʿēd</em>) — the completion notice launches a remarkable literary parallel to Genesis 2:1 ('Thus the heavens and the earth were completed, <em>wayĕkullû</em>'). The same Hebrew root <em>klh</em> (to complete, finish) appears in both; many scholars argue the tabernacle completion narrative is deliberately structured as a new-creation account. Just as God completed creation in seven days, Israel completes the tabernacle through a seven-speech series of divine instructions (Exod 25-31). The tabernacle is the new Eden, YHWH's dwelling-place with humanity restored.</p>",
        "33": "<p>The formal presentation of all the tabernacle components to Moses mirrors the presentation of the completed animals to Adam for naming (Gen 2:19) — another creation-echo. Each component is itemized: clasps, frames, crossbars, pillars, bases, coverings, carrying poles, utensils. The complete inventory demonstrates total compliance with the divine pattern. In ANE temple-dedication texts, the presentation of all cult objects to the deity preceded the deity's taking up residence; here the presentation to Moses (YHWH's representative) precedes YHWH's coming to dwell in the completed sanctuary (40:34-35).</p>",
        "34": "<p>The covering of ram skins dyed red and the covering of fine leather (<em>taḥaš</em> — a marine animal, possibly dugong/sea-cow) formed the waterproof outer covering of the tabernacle. These practical protective layers over the linen inner curtains illustrate the tabernacle's dual nature: an object of extraordinary beauty on the inside (fine linen, gold, precious stones), protected on the outside by utilitarian weatherproofing. The most holy is hidden under the most ordinary — a principle that runs throughout the tabernacle: the glory is inside; the outside is undistinguished.</p>",
        "35": "<p>The ark of the testimony (<em>ʾărōn hāʿēdut</em>) with its mercy seat (<em>kappōret</em>) was the most sacred object in the entire tabernacle complex — the locus of YHWH's presence between the cherubim. The 'testimony' refers to the stone tablets of the Decalogue placed inside the ark (Exod 25:16). The ark was the one object that no one was permitted to touch on pain of death (Num 4:15; 1 Sam 6:19; 2 Sam 6:6-7), carried on poles that were never removed (Exod 25:15), the focal point of the entire priestly service and the reason the tabernacle existed.</p>",
        "36": "<p>The table of the bread of the Presence (<em>šulḥan leḥem happānîm</em>) in the holy place held twelve loaves arranged in two rows of six, changed weekly (Lev 24:5-9). 'Bread of the Presence' (<em>leḥem happānîm</em>, literally 'bread of the face/presence') was food placed before YHWH's face — not as nourishment for the deity (a Mesopotamian concept) but as a symbol of the covenant meal maintained between YHWH and Israel. Twelve loaves = twelve tribes; the table maintained in perpetuity = YHWH's ongoing covenantal provision. The bread was eaten by the priests after being replaced, making every Sabbath a covenant meal.</p>",
        "37": "<p>The gold lampstand (<em>mĕnōrāh</em>) — beaten from a single talent of pure gold — provided the only light in the windowless holy place. Its seven-branched form, with central shaft and three pairs of arms, may represent the cosmic tree (a common ANE motif) or simply the number seven as the symbol of divine completeness. The lampstand's light in the perpetually dark holy place creates the image of divine light sustaining YHWH's own house. Zechariah's vision of the golden lampstand with seven lamps (Zech 4:1-14) interprets it as representing the Spirit of YHWH. Revelation's seven lampstands (Rev 1:12-13, 20) represent the seven churches — the lampstand of the holy place now distributed to the church.</p>",
        "38": "<p>The golden incense altar (<em>mizbaḥ hazzāhāb</em> or <em>mizbaḥ haqqĕtōret</em>) stood directly before the inner veil separating the holy place from the most holy place — the closest human-accessible point to the ark and mercy seat. Incense was burned morning and evening (Exod 30:7-8), creating a constant cloud of fragrant smoke that rose toward YHWH. In ANE temple practice, incense was understood as carrying prayer upward to the deity; the tabernacle incense symbolized Israel's prayers perpetually ascending to YHWH. Revelation 8:3-4 makes this explicit: the angel's incense represents 'the prayers of all the saints.'</p>",
        "39": "<p>The bronze altar (<em>mizbaḥ haNĕḥōšet</em>) stood at the entrance to the tabernacle court — the first object encountered when entering the sanctuary. Its position was theologically precise: access to YHWH begins at the altar of sacrifice. The burned offerings consumed there constituted Israel's fundamental act of worship; no other approach to the tabernacle was possible without passing the altar. The NT interprets Jesus's death as the ultimate fulfillment of the sacrificial altar (Heb 13:10-12; Rev 8:3), making Christ himself the altar through whom the new covenant community approaches God.</p>",
        "40": "<p>The laver (basin, <em>kiyyôr</em>) and its bronze stand were placed between the altar and the tabernacle entrance. Priests were required to wash hands and feet before entering the tent or approaching the altar (Exod 30:19-21; 40:31-32). The washing was not optional; failure to wash brought death (Exod 30:20). The sequence — altar (atonement) then laver (purification) then tabernacle (access) — built the theology of approach into the physical architecture. John's Gospel's emphasis on washing (John 13:1-17) and the NT's baptismal theology draw on this architectural logic of purification preceding sacred presence.</p>",
        "41": "<p>'The woven vestments for serving in the sanctuary, the sacred garments for Aaron the priest, and the garments for his sons' — the final item in the inventory is the garments, now completed. Their listing last is deliberately climactic: the garments described in exhaustive detail in vv.1-31 are now presented to Moses as the final component of the complete system. The phrase 'for serving in the sanctuary (<em>lĕšārēt baqqōdeš</em>)' recalls the unique character of the priestly office: they do not serve an institution or a building but serve in the sacred — in the holy space that belongs to YHWH.</p>",
        "42": "<p>'The Israelites had done all the work exactly as the LORD had commanded Moses' (<em>kĕkol ʾăšer ṣiwwāh YHWH ʾet-mōšeh kēn ʿāśû bĕnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) — this summary verse uses the phrase 'just as the LORD commanded Moses' for the last time in the chapter (it appears seven times in vv.32-43). The same phrase appears five times in ch.40 (vv.16, 19, 21, 23, 25, 27, 29, 32). The total count is twelve in these two chapters — one for each tribe? The literary structure insists: this is covenant obedience, not artistic improvisation. The tabernacle is the physical embodiment of Israel doing exactly what YHWH said.</p>",
        "43": "<p>'Moses inspected all the work and saw that they had done it just as the LORD commanded. And Moses blessed them' (<em>waybārek ʾōtām mōšeh</em>) — Moses's blessing of Israel after the tabernacle's completion echoes God's blessing of creation at its completion (Gen 1:28; 2:3). Moses is acting in the role of the Creator-God in this new-creation narrative: he inspects, approves, and blesses. The completion of the tabernacle is the end of one epoch (the exodus, Sinai covenant, construction) and the beginning of another (YHWH dwelling in Israel's midst). It is, in the narrative's theology, the restoration of Eden — YHWH walking among his people in a sanctified garden.</p>"
    },
    "40": {
        "1": "<p>The divine command to erect the tabernacle comes after the completion of all its components. The divine speech initiating the tabernacle's dedication mirrors the divine speech of the creation week in Genesis 1 — the same structure: YHWH speaks, Moses obeys, the result matches the command. The entire chapter is structured by the repeated 'as the LORD commanded Moses' formula, creating a liturgical repetition that emphasizes perfect obedience. The tabernacle dedication is not just a historical event but a theological statement about the nature of worship: it is initiated and specified by YHWH, not improvised by humans.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'On the first day of the first month' — the first day of Nisan (Abib) was the New Year's Day of the religious calendar in Israel. The tabernacle was erected on New Year's Day of the second year after the exodus — a date of extraordinary symbolic weight: the new year of Israel's new life in covenant with YHWH begins with the erection of YHWH's dwelling. The New Year timing ties the tabernacle's inauguration to the seasonal cycle of new beginning and to the anniversary of the exodus (Passover is on 14 Nisan, just two weeks later). The first day of creation (Gen 1:1-5) resonates with the first day of the covenant sanctuary's life.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The placement of the ark before the inner veil is the first act of furnishing — the most sacred object in the most sacred location. The order proceeds from the most holy outward: ark first (most holy place), then lampstand and table (holy place), then incense altar, then bronze altar (outer court). This inside-out order of installation mirrors the graduated holiness of the sanctuary: work begins at YHWH's throne and moves outward to the human periphery, rather than building up from the outside in. The veil (<em>pārokēt</em>) that screens the ark was the same that was torn at the crucifixion (Matt 27:51; Heb 10:20).</p>",
        "4": "<p>The table of the bread of the Presence is placed and the bread 'arranged' (<em>wĕʿāraktā</em>) — literally 'set in order' — before YHWH. The word <em>ʿārak</em> is the same verb used for arranging battle lines ('setting in order' for combat) and for preparing a fire (arranging the wood). The bread of the Presence is not merely left on the table but formally arranged in prescribed order (two rows of six, Lev 24:6), an act of service that acknowledges YHWH as the host who receives this perpetual covenant table-setting. The lampstand is lit simultaneously — the holy place now has both light and food, a prepared room awaiting its occupant.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The golden incense altar before the inner veil and the screen at the tabernacle's entrance complete the holy place furnishings. The deliberate positioning of the incense altar 'before the ark of the testimony' (with only the inner veil between them) placed the prayer-symbolizing incense as the final human approach before YHWH's throne. In the ANE, the approach to a throne room typically involved a series of increasingly restricted spaces; the tabernacle architecture embodies this universal principle in a covenant-specific form. Access to the presence requires passing each threshold in order: court, holy place, most holy place.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The bronze altar's position 'at the entrance to the tabernacle' establishes the unavoidable priority of sacrifice in approaching YHWH. Before anyone can pass into the tabernacle proper, they must pass the place of sacrifice. The spatial theology is unambiguous: there is no access to YHWH without atonement. This architectural logic is the background for Hebrews' argument about Christ's priestly work: 'We have an altar from which those who minister at the tabernacle have no right to eat' (Heb 13:10). The NT reinterprets the bronze altar's position in terms of the cross as the necessary threshold for approach to God.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The laver ('basin,' <em>kiyyôr</em>) between the tent and the altar occupies the liminal zone between sacrifice (altar) and the divine dwelling (tent). Its position is architecturally significant: after sacrifice (atonement for sin) comes washing (purification for holiness). The two stages — blood for guilt, water for impurity — correspond to the two dimensions of the human problem before a holy God: moral guilt requiring substitutionary sacrifice, and ritual impurity requiring cleansing. The NT's baptismal theology draws on this distinction: 'the washing of regeneration' (Titus 3:5) follows the 'blood that cleanses from all sin' (1 John 1:7).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The 'surrounding court' (<em>ḥăṣar</em>) enclosed the entire tabernacle complex within a rectangular courtyard (100 cubits × 50 cubits; Exod 27:9-19). The court's entrance faced east, placing the tabernacle's inner entrance facing east toward the sunrise — a common orientation in ancient sacred architecture (Egyptian temples, Mesopotamian ziggurats, and later Solomon's temple all faced east). Israel's camp surrounded the court on all four sides (Num 2), with the tribes arranged by compass point. The entire camp was organized around the tabernacle as its center, with YHWH's presence radiating outward through the graduated holiness zones.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The anointing of the tabernacle with the sacred anointing oil (<em>šemen hammiš-ḥāh</em>) — a unique formula of olive oil with myrrh, cinnamon, calamus, and cassia (Exod 30:22-25) — consecrated it from an extraordinary human construction to YHWH's actual dwelling. The verb <em>māšaḥ</em> (to anoint) gives the noun <em>māšîaḥ</em> (messiah/anointed one). The tabernacle and its furnishings are 'anointed' and thus 'holy' (<em>qādôš</em>) — set apart for YHWH's exclusive use. The same formula applies to the priests (vv.13-15). The anointed sanctuary and the anointed priests together constitute the covenant worship system.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The altar's anointing is described separately and its result is distinctive: 'it will become most holy (<em>qōdeš qŏdāšîm</em>)' — the superlative degree of holiness, the same phrase used for the most holy place (the inner sanctuary). The altar of burnt offering was not the most hidden object but it occupied the most holy category because it was the place of sacrifice — the intersection of human guilt and divine acceptance. 'Whatever touches it will become holy' — the altar's holiness was contagious outward, not merely defensive inward. Whatever legitimate contact with the altar made one holy; illegitimate contact with it meant death (Num 4:15).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The laver's consecration completes the anointing sequence. The basin and stand are consecrated separately — emphasizing that the instrument of purification is itself pure, not merely functional. The anointing of the laver with the same sacred oil used on the altar and the tabernacle itself integrates the washing station into the fully consecrated sanctuary system. The laver was not a utility item added for hygienic reasons but a theological instrument integrated into the covenant worship architecture from its inception.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance of the tent of meeting and wash them with water' — the priests' consecration begins with washing, not garbing: the physical body is cleansed before it is dressed in holy garments. The sequence (washing → clothing → anointing → consecration) is a ritual biography: the priest is remade through these acts from an ordinary Israelite into YHWH's covenant servant. The entrance of the tent of meeting is the threshold space — the liminal point between ordinary space and sacred space — where the transformation is enacted. Later ordination rites in Lev 8 follow the same sequence in detail.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Aaron alone receives both the sacred garments (the full high priestly vestiture of ch.39) and anointing. The anointing of the high priest is the paradigmatic act that generates the word <em>māšîaḥ</em> (anointed): Aaron is Israel's first 'messiah' in the technical sense — YHWH's anointed mediator between the divine and human realms. David and subsequent Israelite kings will also be anointed, expanding the concept from priestly to royal mediators. Jesus as the final Messiah combines both offices (priest and king) in one person, fulfilling both streams of the anointed-mediator tradition (Heb 7:1-3: king and priest like Melchizedek).</p>",
        "14": "<p>Aaron's sons receive the simpler vestiture of the ordinary priests — tunics only, not the full regalia of the high priest. Their role was to assist in the sacrificial system without entering the most holy place or wearing the breastplate, ephod, or golden plate. The graduated vestiture reflected the graduated responsibilities: high priest once a year in the most holy place; ordinary priests daily in the holy place and court; Levites in the outer camp without entering the tent. The differentiated system was not rank-for-its-own-sake but functional — different degrees of approach required different degrees of sanctification.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'Their anointing will be to establish a perpetual priesthood for the generations to come' — the anointing creates an enduring institution, not just individual consecration. The phrase 'perpetual priesthood' (<em>kĕhunnāt ʿôlām</em>) echoes Phinehas's covenant of a perpetual priesthood (Num 25:13) and becomes the basis for the Aaronic priesthood's ongoing authority. Hebrews directly engages this perpetual priesthood claim: the Aaronic priesthood was indeed perpetual in type — pointing forward to the final high priest, Jesus, whose priesthood 'is not by a law of fleshly lineage but by the power of an indestructible life' (Heb 7:16), making it truly eternal rather than generationally renewed.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'Moses did everything just as the LORD had commanded him' (<em>wayyaʿaś mōšeh kĕkōl ʾăšer ṣiwwāh YHWH ʾōtô kēn ʿāśāh</em>) — the summary obedience statement introduces the installation narrative. This formula appears six more times in the chapter (vv.19, 21, 23, 25, 27, 29, 32), creating a rhythmic refrain that identifies Moses's act of installation as perfect covenant compliance. The repetition is liturgical, not literary laziness: each echo reinforces that the tabernacle's creation and inauguration are acts of covenantal obedience, not human innovation. The sanctuary exists because YHWH commanded it and Israel obeyed.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'On the first day of the first month of the second year' — the precise date marks the tabernacle's erection as a historically significant and publicly remembered event. The second year's first day is exactly nine months after the covenant at Sinai (which occurred on the first day of the third month, Exod 19:1). In those nine months: the Law was given, the covenant was ratified, the golden calf apostasy occurred, Moses interceded and received the second tablets, and the tabernacle was constructed. The nine-month gestation metaphor is not accidental — Israel was 'born' as a covenant people at Sinai and the tabernacle marks the newborn's first home.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Moses himself erects the tabernacle — setting the bases, frames, crossbars, and pillars in the precise order the instructions specified. This detail is significant: Moses is not merely a supervisor but a hands-on installer of the sanctuary. The founding leader personally establishes the community's central institution. The parallel is to Adam who was placed in the garden to 'work it and keep it' (<em>lĕʿobdāh ûlĕšomrāh</em>, Gen 2:15) — to maintain the divine dwelling-space as its first administrator. Moses as the second-Adam figure in this new Eden-narrative does the same.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Moses spreads the tent covering over the tabernacle frame and lays the outer covers — working from the top down, enclosing the sacred space. The outer covering of animal skins that protected the sanctuary's beauty from weather is an image that recurs in prophetic and apocalyptic contexts: the veil that hides the divine glory from undiscerning eyes. Isaiah 25:7 speaks of the 'veil that veils all peoples' being removed on YHWH's mountain; Paul speaks of the veil over Moses's face removed 'in Christ' (2 Cor 3:14-16). The tabernacle's outer covering is the first instance of hidden-but-present glory — outwardly unimpressive, inwardly magnificent.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The tablets of the testimony (<em>hāʿēdut</em>) are placed inside the ark before the mercy seat is put on. The order is precise: testimony (the Decalogue) in the ark first, then the mercy seat on top — so the blood sprinkled on the mercy seat on Yom Kippur (Lev 16:14-15) covers the testimony. The spatial relationship is intentionally designed: the law's demands (<em>ʿēdut</em>) are beneath the atonement cover (<em>kappōret</em>). Paul argues this exact spatial theology in Romans 3:25: Christ is the <em>hilastērion</em> (mercy seat/propitiation) — the blood of Christ over the demands of the law, satisfying its claims.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Bringing the ark into the tabernacle and hanging the inner veil to screen it off is the single act of greatest theological gravity in the entire installation: YHWH's throne-object is now in its place, and the veil separates it from human approach. The veil (<em>pārokēt</em>) made of blue, purple, scarlet, and linen (Exod 26:31) was 'for the separation' (<em>lĕhābdîl</em>) — the same word used in Genesis 1 for YHWH's separating acts in creation. The veil in the tabernacle is the creaturely counterpart to the cosmic boundaries YHWH established: it marks the place where the holy and the common must not be confused.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The table is placed on the north side of the holy place, outside the inner veil — accessible to the priests but not to ordinary Israelites. The directional placement (north for the table, south for the lampstand, v.24) is not explained in the text; traditions regarding the cosmic significance of these directions are preserved in later Jewish literature. North was associated in some ANE cosmologies with the divine mountain (Ps 48:2: 'the far north... the city of the Great King'); the north side of the temple complex in later Judaism became associated with the table of the divine presence receiving Israel's covenant offering.</p>",
        "23": "<p>'He arranged the bread on the table before the LORD' — the bread of the Presence is set 'before YHWH' (<em>lipnê YHWH</em>), formally constituting the sacred meal that the tabernacle maintains in perpetuity. In ANE temples, the daily offerings of food to the deity were standard practice; the bread of the Presence in Israel's tabernacle transforms this widespread practice: the twelve loaves represent not food for YHWH but Israel's ongoing covenant presence before him. YHWH does not eat the bread (the priests eat it, Lev 24:9); rather, the bread is the weekly renewal of the covenant relationship — Israel's table before YHWH, acknowledging him as their host.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The lampstand on the south side of the holy place opposite the table creates a bilateral symmetry: bread/table (north) and light/lampstand (south) face each other across the holy place. The lampstand's seven lights are the only illumination in the holy place; extinguishing them would have left the sacred space in total darkness. The perpetual burning of the lampstand (Exod 27:20-21: 'a lamp that burns continually') symbolized YHWH's continuous presence and the priest's continuous worship — a flame that never went out representing a relationship that never ended.</p>",
        "25": "<p>Moses lights the lamps — literally 'caused the lamps to go up' (<em>wayyaʿal hannērōt</em>) — the same verb used for offering burnt offerings. The kindling of the lamps is an act of worship equivalent to sacrifice. The lampstand's lights in the windowless holy place are the only light by which the priests can see the table, the incense altar, and their work — a reminder that all service in YHWH's presence depends on YHWH's own light rather than natural illumination. John's Gospel applies this to Christ: 'The true light that gives light to everyone was coming into the world' (John 1:9).</p>",
        "26": "<p>The golden incense altar in front of the inner veil is the final piece of holy-place furniture. Its position — as close to the ark as possible without passing the veil — made it the threshold object: here the priest stood at the furthest point of legitimate human access on ordinary days. The incense altar in the holy place and the ark in the most holy place are functionally coupled: on Yom Kippur, the high priest took coals from this altar into the most holy place to burn incense before the mercy seat, creating a cloud of smoke under which he performed the blood rite (Lev 16:12-13). The altar is the launching point for the closest approach to YHWH.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The burning of aromatic incense completes the holy place activation: the room now has light (lampstand), covenantal provision (table with bread), and ascending prayer (incense). The three elements of the holy place — light, bread, incense — correspond to three fundamental theological realities: YHWH as the source of illumination (light), YHWH as the one who feeds his covenant people (bread), and Israel's ongoing communication with YHWH (incense as prayer). The holy place is not a storage room but a living theological environment maintained daily by priestly service.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The screen at the tabernacle's entrance (<em>māsāk pettaḥ hāʾōhel</em>) marked the threshold between the outer court (accessible to all Israelites after presenting sacrifices) and the holy place (accessible only to priests). The screen — embroidered linen rather than the more elaborately woven inner veil — was the least restricted of the tabernacle's boundaries, but still a boundary. The graduated restriction system (outer court → holy place → most holy place) physically encoded the theology of graduated holiness: access to YHWH is available in degrees proportional to the degree of separation from sin and the world.</p>",
        "29": "<p>The bronze altar in its correct position before the tabernacle entrance completes the court furnishings. Moses then offers burnt offerings and grain offerings — the first sacrifices offered at the completed altar. This inaugural sacrifice formally activates the sacrificial system; the tabernacle is not merely erected but put into immediate liturgical operation. The parallel to the first day of creation (where light is not merely present but operating: 'and there was light') is maintained: the tabernacle's furnishings are installed and immediately functioning, not stored until formally opened.</p>",
        "30": "<p>The bronze laver is filled with water — the first water-filling of the basin that will be refilled daily for priestly hand-and-foot washing. The first filling of the laver is Moses's act, not Aaron's; Moses as the initiating mediator prepares the instrument of priestly purification before the priests who will use it. The bronze laver (<em>kiyyôr nĕḥōšet</em>) was made from the bronze mirrors of the women who served at the tabernacle entrance (Exod 38:8) — weapons of vanity transformed into instruments of purification, an image of worldly self-regard converted into covenant service.</p>",
        "31": "<p>Moses, Aaron, and Aaron's sons are the first to wash at the laver — the founding figures of the covenant worship system performing the inaugural purification. This is the only time Moses is described washing at the laver; subsequently it will be Aaron and his sons who wash as their regular covenant obligation (Exod 30:19-20). Moses washes here as the covenant mediator who inaugurates the system, before handing the ongoing responsibility to the Aaronic priests. The transition is subtle but significant: Moses establishes; Aaron administers.</p>",
        "32": "<p>'Whenever they entered the tent of meeting or approached the altar, they washed — just as the LORD had commanded Moses' — the washing is not a one-time purification but an ongoing requirement before every entry into sacred space. Ritual impurity accumulated in ordinary life; the laver was the constant reset. This principle — that human life in the world produces spiritual impurity requiring regular cleansing before approaching the holy — underlies both the elaborate Levitical purity system and the NT's emphasis on ongoing confession and cleansing (1 John 1:9: 'If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness').</p>",
        "33": "<p>Moses completes the court installation — curtains, altar, screen — and with this last act 'Moses finished the work' (<em>waykkal mōšeh ʾet-hamĕlāʾkāh</em>). The verb <em>kālāh</em> and the noun <em>mĕlāʾkāh</em> (work/craftsmanship) are the precise vocabulary of Genesis 2:2 ('And God finished the work that he had done'). The creation-echo is now explicit: Moses finishing the tabernacle work echoes YHWH finishing the creation work. The tabernacle is the new creation; Moses in completing it acts in the role of the Creator completing his cosmos. The Sabbath rest of creation is replaced by the divine indwelling that follows in v.34.</p>",
        "34": "<p>'Then the cloud covered the tent of meeting, and the glory of the LORD (<em>kĕbôd YHWH</em>) filled the tabernacle' — this is the theological climax of the entire book of Exodus. Everything since ch.1 — the slavery, the plagues, the Passover, the Red Sea, Sinai, the Law, the golden calf, the renewal, the tabernacle construction — has been moving toward this moment: YHWH taking up permanent residence among his people. The cloud filling the tabernacle echoes the cloud that covered Sinai (19:16-18; 24:15-16); the glory (<em>kābôd</em>) that filled the mountain now fills the portable sanctuary. What was fixed at Sinai becomes mobile with Israel.</p>",
        "35": "<p>'Moses was unable to enter the tent of meeting, because the cloud had settled on it and the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle' — even Moses, who had spoken with YHWH 'face to face' (Exod 33:11), could not enter when the fullness of the divine glory occupied the space. The overwhelming presence that made the cloud impenetrable for Moses is the same glory that Paul describes as 'unapproachable light, whom no one has seen or can see' (1 Tim 6:16). The first function of the tabernacle after YHWH's glory fills it is to demonstrate that no human, however close to YHWH, can stand in the fullness of divine presence on human terms.</p>",
        "36": "<p>The cloud-lifting signal for Israel's movement (<em>bĕhēʿālôt hĕʿānān meʿal hammiš-kān yisĕʿû bĕnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) connects the end of Exodus directly to the wilderness narrative in Numbers (Num 9:15-23 elaborates this same system in detail). The tabernacle is not a stationary sanctuary but a portable one: YHWH moves with his people, and the people move when YHWH's presence moves. The cloud-guidance system — lift = march, settle = camp — put the entire military-strategic movement of two million people under direct divine direction. No human general, not even Moses, chose the route; YHWH's visible presence determined every march.</p>",
        "37": "<p>'But if the cloud did not lift, they did not set out — not until the day it lifted' — the passive obedience to divine timing is as significant as the active obedience of marching. Israel waited when YHWH remained; they moved when YHWH moved. The waiting could have been a day or a year (Num 9:22: 'whether two days or a month or longer'). This total dependence on divine timing for movement is the theological counterpart to the Sabbath rest: YHWH sets the rhythm of both rest and march, as he set the rhythm of creation. Human impatience and YHWH's chosen pace are in constant tension throughout the wilderness narrative.</p>",
        "38": "<p>'The cloud of the LORD rested on the tabernacle by day, and fire glowed in the cloud by night, in the sight of all the house of Israel throughout all their journeys' — the final verse of Exodus restates the pillar of cloud and fire (13:21-22) in its new, tabernacle-centered form. What began as a pillar guiding the march is now the cloud dwelling on the completed sanctuary. The ending <em>bĕkol massĕʿêhem</em> ('throughout all their journeys') looks forward: Exodus ends before the journey to the promised land is complete, but it ends with the guarantee of YHWH's presence for the entire journey. The book of wandering begins with the assurance that YHWH will be there.</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', existing)
    for ch in ['39', '40']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with context commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
